WEBVTT

00:00:00.300 --> 00:00:02.300
Hey there, future web developers.

00:00:02.980 --> 00:00:08.700
Did you know JavaScript has several ways to display data? Whether you're updating a web page or testing code,

00:00:09.300 --> 00:00:15.340
JavaScript's got you covered. Let's break it down into four simple methods. Quick and easy, just like we like it.

00:00:17.460 --> 00:00:20.100
First up, using inner HTML.

00:00:20.700 --> 00:00:22.860
This is like filling in a shape or form.

00:00:23.660 --> 00:00:27.180
JavaScript finds an existing element by its ID and updates the content.

00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:31.290
Here's how it works.

00:00:31.290 --> 00:00:35.690
This code grabs the p-tag with the ID demo and changes its content to...

00:00:36.370 --> 00:00:38.050
You guessed it.

00:00:38.050 --> 00:00:39.650
Hello world!

00:00:39.650 --> 00:00:42.290
Super handy for updating content dynamically.

00:00:43.530 --> 00:00:45.530
Next we have document write.

00:00:46.050 --> 00:00:51.410
It's like the loudspeaker of JavaScript. It outputs directly into the HTML document.

00:00:51.890 --> 00:00:59.900
But watch out. If you use document write after the page has loaded, it wipes out everything on your page.

00:01:00.380 --> 00:01:02.380
See this example.

00:01:03.140 --> 00:01:05.500
Here we run the code when the user clicks the button.

00:01:06.020 --> 00:01:11.500
So after the page has finished loading, oops, it replaces our entire page.

00:01:12.740 --> 00:01:15.580
So great for quick testing, but not for production.

00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:18.460
Want to grab someone's attention?

00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:23.500
Use an alert box with window alert or just alert since the window part is optional.

00:01:23.940 --> 00:01:33.290
This pops up a box with the result. Great for quick notifications, but don't overuse it unless you like annoying your users.

00:01:35.840 --> 00:01:39.760
And finally, the secret weapon for debugging, console, log.

00:01:40.280 --> 00:01:45.080
Think of it like a journal for your code. It logs messages straight to the browser console.

00:01:47.090 --> 00:01:52.890
Use this to test your code behind the scenes without interrupting the user experience. It's a developer's best friend.

00:01:55.020 --> 00:02:01.180
When testing console methods, you need to have the console view visible. This is usually opened by pressing F12.

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:05.520
One last trick.

00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:11.360
While JavaScript doesn't have a direct send to printer function, you can use window print to print the current page.

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:18.240
Easy peasy. Just one button click and voila. Old timey paper printed content.

00:02:19.200 --> 00:02:27.800
So there you have it. Four ways to display data in JavaScript plus a bonus printing tip. Try them out and see which one works best for your projects.

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:35.400
Thanks for watching. Like and subscribe to get notified about our latest videos. For more coding tips and tricks,

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:38.800
keep it locked right here on w3schools.com.

00:02:39.280 --> 00:02:43.440
Don't forget to try out what you've learned in our interactive editor. Happy coding.
